com.vector.cfg.model.access

Interface IModelAccess


  • @PublishedApi(value=ADDITIONS_ALLOWED)
public interface IModelAccess

    IModelAccess

    The IModelAccess is a basic model service which collects several general access utility methods. The most basic are:
    • getAutosarRoot(): Returns the root object of the AUTOSAR data model tree
    • getImmediateParent(MIObject): Returns the parent object of the specified instance
    • getAllInstancesOfType(Class): Returns all MDF instances of the specified type

    Module configuration and module definition handling

    • getModuleConfiguration(MIObject): Returns the module configuration (parent) object of an ECUC object like containers, for example
    • getModuleDefinition(MIObject): Returns the module definition object of an ECUC objects module configuration
    • isRefinedModuleDefinition(String,String): Analyzes module definition refinements
    • getAllWithDefinition(String): Returns all object instances with a specific definition path
    • getAllStandardDefinitions(): Returns all AUTOSAR standard definition
    • getAllModuleDefinitions(): Returns all loaded MIModuleDef module definitions

    Get child objects by definition

    The following methods navigate through the ECUC model tree and returns objects of the specified definition type:
    • getChildByDefinition(MIHasContainer,String)
    • getChildrenByDefinition(MIHasContainer,String)
    • getContainerByDefinition(MIHasContainer,String)
    • getContainersByDefinition(MIHasContainer,String)
    • getParentContainerByDefinition(MIHasDefinition,String)
    • getParentByDefinition(MIHasDefinition,String)
    • getParameterByDefinition(MIContainer,String)
    • getParametersByDefinition(MIContainer,String)
    The String argument is an absolute or relative definition path. These get-methods also exists in overloaded variants with a DefRef argument instead of the definition string.
    • An absolute definition path is for example: "/MICROSAR/Com/ComGeneral/ComVersionInfoApi"
    • A relative definition path is for example: "ComGeneral/ComVersionInfoApi" (as child object of the Com module configuration) or just ComVersionInfoApi (as child object of the ComGeneral container)

    Parameter value handling

    The following methods provide access to integer parameters:
    • containsInteger(MINumericalValue): Checks if the specified parameter really contains an integer value. That's useful since the ARXML file may contain any string in the VALUE tag of a parameter
    • getAsInteger(MINumericalValue)
    • setAsInteger(MINumericalValue,BigInteger)
    Similar methods exist for boolean, float and string parameter types.

    Object links

    An object link is a string which identifies a model object as good as possible. The object link can be used in reports or log entries. It cannot be used reliably to retrieve model objects because they are ambiguous under specific circumstances. The most simple case of an object link is the AUTOSAR path of an MIReferrable object. This is, for example, the object link of a container in the ECUC:
    /ActiveEcuC/Can/CanConfigSet/CanHardwareObject For being able to provide meaningful object links for parameters also, the AUTOSAR path of their parent container gets a postfix which specifies the parameter instance. This postfix is a combination of the parameters definition shortname and the positional index in the list of parameters with the same definition below their parent container:
    /ActiveEcuC/Can/CanConfigSet/CanHardwareObject[0:CanControllerRef] The object link of an object can be retrieved with AsrObjectLink
    To simplify handling of invisible objects, some model services provide model access even for invisible objects in variant projects. The affected classes and interfaces are:
    • ModelUtil
    • ModelAccessUtil
    • IReferrableAccess
    • IModelAccess
    • IModelCompareService
    • DefRef
    • AsrPath
    • IEcucDefinitionAccess (all methods which deal with configuration side objects)
    Only a subset of the methods in these services work with invisible objects (read the methods JavaDoc for details). The general policy to select exactly these methods was:
    • Support access to type and object identity of MDF objects (definition and AUTOSAR path)
    • Parameter value or other content related information must still be retrieved in a context the object is visible in
    • Also not contained are methods which change model content. E.g. deleting invisible objects, set parameter values, ...

    This ProjectService is threadsafe

    • Field Detail

      • NUMBER_OF_BITS_IN_A_LONG

        @PublishedField
static final int NUMBER_OF_BITS_IN_A_LONG
        This constant value is being used within the model and persistency components to represent unlimited integer values (e.g. for upper multiplicity "*"). The value is (2^64 + Long.MAX_VALUE) guarantees the following behavior:
        • It is larger than any integer value valid for AUTOSAR.
        • If someone tries to convert this value to a native long the result will be Long.MAX_VALUE which can expected to be sufficient for all practical cases like large upper-multiplicity values
        See Also:
        Constant Field Values

      • getAllInstancesOfType

        @PublishedMethod
<T extends MIObject> java.util.Collection<T> getAllInstancesOfType(java.lang.Class<T> type)
        Returns all MDF instances of the specified type.

        Please use getAllModuleDefinitions()}.values() instead of getAllInstancesOfType(MIModuleDef.class) for performance reasons!

        Be aware that retrieving object instances this way is only fast for a small number of expected instances. If you expect a large number of objects and/or large inheritance trees of the specified type (e.g. retrieving all instances of MIARRef) it is probably much faster traversing the complete model tree. The point here is that this method internally builds a set of instances and adds all sets of instances of the derived types. All together means handling a huge amount of hash-sets.
        SO - USE THIS METHOD CAREFULLY!

        Parameters:
        type - to search for.
        Returns:
        Collection of found elements.

      • getAllWithDefinition

        @PublishedMethod
java.util.List<com.vector.cfg.model.mdf.model.autosar.ecucdescription.MIHasDefinition> getAllWithDefinition(java.lang.String definitionPath)
        This method searches for all objects with the specified definition path within the active module configurations. This definition path may also use a refined module definition path. The method investigates all refinements to find matching definitions in the active configurations.

        Example: If the specified definition path is and AUTOSAR standard definition, it will also find objects within refined modules. So "/AUTOSAR/Can/CanGeneral" will also find objects with definition "/MICROSAR/Can/CanGeneral".

        If the specified definition path is a relative path, it must start with a module definitions base short-name. Nevertheless this method also finds differing module definition names of refined module definitions.

        • "Can/CanGeneral" will find objects with definition "/MICROSAR/Can/CanGeneral" but "CanGeneral" will find nothing!
        • "/AUTOSAR/Can" or simply "Can" will find all active Can module configurations

        Remark: If the returned child objects are immediate children of the specified parent, their order is the same as in the MDF model.

        Parameters:
        definitionPath - is an absolute or relative AUTOSAR definition path
        Returns:

      • getParameterType

        @PublishedMethod
EParameterType getParameterType(com.vector.cfg.model.mdf.model.autosar.ecucdescription.MIParameterValue param)
        AUTOSAR doesn't define the parameter type in the parameter instance but in its definition. But the definition may not be available (e.g. bswmd file is missing). Even if we had the definition available within the project, the persistency had no access to it during model load because it could be contained in a file which would be loaded later.

        To support convenient parameter access this method tries to detect the specific parameter type.

        Remark: This method also works for invisible MDF objects (see the documentation of IModelAccess for details).

        Parameters:
        param - is a configuration parameter instance
        Returns:
        Throws:
        java.lang.NullPointerException - if the parameter is null

      • isConsistentWithDefType

        @PublishedMethod
boolean isConsistentWithDefType(com.vector.cfg.model.mdf.model.autosar.ecucdescription.MINumericalValue param)
        Checks if the specified parameters value is consistent with its type as specified in its definition. If e.g. the parameters definition specifies the type as an integer this method checks if it really contains an integer.

        You can use this function before reading a numeric value to check if the parameter has a definition and the value matches the definition. Calling the related get-method afterwards will never lead to an error if this method returned true. Special cases:

        • If the parameter contains no value (the value string is null or empty), this method returns false
        • If the definition reference cannot be resolved, this method returns false
        In all other cases it returns true if the value matches its definition and false else.
        Parameters:
        param - is an AUTOSAR numerical parameter
        Returns:

        @KeepSecretFromPublishedApi
 @Deprecated
boolean isCreateableChild(com.vector.cfg.model.mdf.model.autosar.ecucdescription.MIHasContainer parent,
                                                                     java.lang.String childDefinition,
                                                                     java.lang.String shortName,
                                                                     boolean childAlreadyExists)
        Deprecated. 
        This method checks if a child object with the specified definition can be created. There are several possible reasons why this may not be the case:
        • The CE itself is not changeable (for whatever reason, e.g. because the related file is read-only)
        • The definition doesn't exist below this CE
        • The specified shortname is not valid or already used for a child object of this CE
        Be aware that this method doesn't check the multiplicity of child objects. The user shall not be restricted to create even inconsistent model contents as long as we can technically store them and make them persistent. All inconsistencies will later be reported by the consistency component in either case.
        Parameters:
        parent - is the new childs parent object
        childDefinition - AUTOSAR definition ref of the child CE
        shortName - shortname of the child. In case of a parameter, this string will be ignored and may be null
        childAlreadyExists - is true if this method is called after creation of the child object. In this case the method accepts that the specified shortname already exists
        Returns:
        true if the child is creatable.

      • isRefinedModuleDefinition

        @PublishedMethod
boolean isRefinedModuleDefinition(java.lang.String moduleDefPath,
                                                    java.lang.String refinedDefPath)
        Returns true if the specified module definition path is a refinement of the specified refined definition path.

        Example

        • The module definition path /MICROSAR/Can_CanoeemuCanoe/Can is a refinement of /AUTOSAR/Can
        • The module definition path /AUTOSAR/Can is also a refinement of /AUTOSAR/Can
        • The module definition path /MICROSAR/Dem is not a refinement of /AUTOSAR/Can
        Parameters:
        moduleDefPath -
        Returns:
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalStateException - if the refinement cannot be analyzed (e.g. because the module definition object is missing)

      • matchesDefinition

        @PublishedMethod
boolean matchesDefinition(com.vector.cfg.model.mdf.model.autosar.ecucdescription.MIHasDefinition hasDef,
                                            DefRef defRef)
        Returns true if the specified objects definition matches the specified defRef. This method also supports refinements, so a defRef containing an AUTOSAR definition also matches refined MIRCOSAR objects. Be aware that ad defRef containing an AUTOSAR-wildcard doesn't match MIRCOSAR definitions because the wildcard semantic doesn't support refinement checks!

        hasDef -
        defRef -
        Returns:

      • matchesDefinition

        @PublishedMethod
boolean matchesDefinition(com.vector.cfg.model.mdf.model.autosar.ecucdescription.MIHasDefinition hasDef,
                                            java.lang.String definition)
        Returns true if the specified objects definition matches the specified definition. This method also supports refinements, so an AUTOSAR definition also matches refined MIRCOSAR objects. Concerning the specified definition two cases are supported:
        1. Absolute definition path: In this case the complete definition is matched and module refinements are supported
        2. Relative definition path: In this case the definition is assumed to be the last short name of the specified objects definition. Nothing else is checked.

        Remark: This method also works for invisible MDF objects (see the documentation of IModelAccess for details).

        Parameters:
        hasDef -
        definition -
        Returns:

      • setParameterValue

        @PublishedMethod
<DEF extends com.vector.cfg.model.mdf.model.autosar.ecucparamdef.MIConfigParameter,CFG extends com.vector.cfg.model.mdf.model.autosar.ecucdescription.MIParameterValue,VAL> void setParameterValue(TypedDefRef<DEF,CFG,VAL> defRef,
                                                                                                                                                                                                                     CFG parameterToSet,
                                                                                                                                                                                                                     VAL newValue)
        Sets the value (newValue) of the passed parameter (parameterToSet). The method is fully typesafe and checked.

        Attention: InstancesReferences are currently NOT supported!
        Attention: AddInfo are currently NOT supported!

        Type Parameters:
        DEF - the generic type
        CFG - the generic type
        VAL - the generic type
        Parameters:
        defRef - the DefRef of the parameterToSet. This DefRef is used for type checks!
        parameterToSet - the MIParameterValue which shall be used to set the new value.
        newValue - the new value of the Parameter
        Throws:
        java.lang.NullPointerException -
        • if the defRef parameter is null
        • if the parameterToSet parameter is null
        • if the newValue parameter is null, and the requested destination type is no String Type.
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException -
        • if the defRef parameter is not the definition of the passed parameterToSet.
        • if the type of the passed parameter is not compatible with the passed newValue.

        Use this feature carefully and be aware that a thread cannot be set to read-write mode afterwards.
